            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1371209855,
            "creation_date": 1371209855,
            "body": "<p>The result is <code>white<\/code>, <strong>because your naming convention is extremely bad<\/strong>. <\/p>\n\n<p>Regardless of the technical reasons other people will/have given you, the sole reason for even thinking about the problem is that you named your variables in such a manner, that you yourself and all other people will have trouble reading and understanding. And the only thing that will have no trouble is the compiler, which is defined strictly enough to know what to do.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 17107599,
            "question_id": 17107384
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3ed59e397350782dbe1450e4e38d959c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 261742,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 546128,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/546128/rasmus-franke",
                "reputation": 4534,
                "display_name": "Rasmus Franke",
                "accept_rate": 76
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1371209504,
            "creation_date": 1371209504,
            "body": "<p>This is a trick question. The class <code>Y<\/code> is never used, <code>static C Y  = new C();<\/code> is an instance of class C named Y and has nothing to do with the class <code>Y<\/code><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 17107507,
            "question_id": 17107384
